4. Datatypes Identification¶

Data Description¶

response_id - Developer's response identification number on the survey

state - State of the developer

state_code - State code of the developer

education - Education of the developer

seniority_level - Level of experience in the field of Data Science

compensation - Salary of developer

avg_age - Approximate age of the developer

language_python - Codes in Python (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

language_r - Codes in R (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

language_sql - Codes in SQL (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

language_bash_shell - Codes in Bash/Shell (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

language_java - Codes in Java (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

language_javascript - Codes in Javascript (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

language_html_css - Codes in HTML/CSS (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

platform_aws - Uses AWS platform (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

platform_gcp - Uses GCP platform (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

platform_azure - Uses Azure platform (0 - No & 1 - Yes)

View all the unique values for all categorical columns.

In [458]:
# Provide unique count values for each categorical column.
for col in categorical_cols:
    print(col)
    i = data[col].unique()
    print(i)
    print(col, 'unique count: ', data[col].nunique())
    print('\n')
    
# Bar chart for number of missing values for all columns.
## Value label function.
def add_value_label(x_list,y_list):
    for i in range(len(x_list)):
        plt.text(i,y_list[i],y_list[i], ha='center', fontsize = 15, bbox = dict(facecolor = 'white', alpha =1.0))
        
## Declare variable for x and y axis.
variables = data[categorical_cols].columns
number_of_unique_values = data[categorical_cols].nunique()

## Plotting cardinality of categorical column.
data[categorical_cols].nunique().plot.bar(figsize=(10,6), color= 'grey', fontsize = 15)

## Attributes of bar chart.
plt.ylabel('Number of Unique Categories', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlabel('Variables', fontsize = 15)
plt.title('Cardinality', fontsize = 15)

## Instantiate value label function. 
add_value_label(variables, number_of_unique_values)

2. % of Rare Categories in Categorical Columns - Data & Chart¶

In [460]:
# Provide count values for each categorical column.
for col in data[categorical_cols]:
    # Bar chart % for each categorical column.
    ((data[col].value_counts()/data[col].shape[0])*100).sort_values(ascending=False).plot.bar(figsize=(14,6), color= 'grey', fontsize = 15)

    # Attributes of bar chart.
    plt.ylabel('% of Categories', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xlabel('Categories: ' + col.capitalize(), fontsize = 15)
    plt.title('% of Categories: ' + col.capitalize(), fontsize = 15)
    plt.axhline(y=3.0, color='red')
    plt.show()
    
    print(col)
    print(round(data[col].value_counts()/data[col].shape[0] * 100, 2).astype(str) + '%')
    print('\n')

Analysis of Rare Categories¶

state_code - California dominates with the highest developers. This seems mainly due to silicon valley. Only 13 states are dominantly based on a 3% threshold. All other states fall into the rare category.

education - Highest number of developers have bachelors or masters. No education categories fall into the rare category.

seniority_level The highest number of developers are experienced. No seniority categories fall into the rare category.

Other Columns - Other columns did not fall into rare category.

# Found lower bound and upper_bound of a variable.
def find_boundaries(data, variable):

    # IQR = Difference between 75% - 25% value.
    IQR = data[variable].quantile(0.75) - data[variable].quantile(0.25)

    # Estimate 1.5 times or 3 times the IQR to calculate.
    lower_boundary = data[variable].quantile(0.25) - (IQR * 1.5)
    upper_boundary = data[variable].quantile(0.75) + (IQR * 1.5)

    return upper_boundary, lower_boundary

 # Provide data & chart for each numerical column.
for col in data[numerical_cols]:
    
    # PLotting box & whisker chart for each numerical column.
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    plt.title(col.capitalize() + ' Data', fontsize = 15)
    sns.boxplot(y = col, data=data, color = 'grey', notch=True)
    sns.stripplot(y = col, data=data, color = 'red')
    plt.ylabel(col, fontsize = 15)
    plt.show()
    
    # PLotting violin chart for each numerical column.
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    plt.title(col.capitalize() + ' Data', fontsize = 15)
    sns.violinplot(y = col, data=data, color = 'grey')
    sns.stripplot(y = col, data=data, color = 'red')
    plt.ylabel(col, fontsize = 15)
    plt.show()
    
    # Calculating lower & upper bound, IQR, count of outlier data, % of outlier data and sample outlier data.
    two_five_pect =  data[col].quantile(0.25)
    seven_five_pect =  data[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = seven_five_pect - two_five_pect
    
    upper_boundary, lower_boundary = find_boundaries(data, col)
    
    outliers = np.where(data[col] > upper_boundary, True,
                    np.where(data[col] < lower_boundary, True, False))
    
    outliers_data = data.loc[outliers, col]

    pect_outlier_data = round((outliers.sum()/data.shape[0] * 100), 2).astype(str) + '%'
    
    # Printing all statistic data.
    print(col.capitalize() + ' Statistics:')
    print('25%: ', two_five_pect)
    print('75%: ', seven_five_pect)
    print('IQR: ', IQR)
    print('upper_boundary: ', upper_boundary)
    print('lower_boundary: ', lower_boundary)
    print('total_outliers: ', outliers.sum())
    print('total_count: ', data.shape[0])
    print('%_of_outlier_data: ', pect_outlier_data)
    
    print('\n')
    print(col.capitalize(), 'Outlier Sample Data:')
    print(outliers_data.head())
